Python beginner notes.

Future import.
from __future__ import << operation >> For example to import division from the future version usefrom __future__ import division.

For the power use 2**3 ==> means 2 power 3

Length
a = 'Get me the length'
len('Get me the length') ==> 17

Indexing - Get me the the char at index

a[0] ==> G
a[1] ==> e

Negative representation of the String. String is like a loop and negative indexing is
possible and will start to pull the elements from the reverse.
a[-1] ==>h (the element of the string). 
however it a[len(a)] or a[-len(a)-1] would result in a array out of index. 

Slicing (pre) a[index:] - Get me all string from the specified index. (similar to substring)
a[1:] ==> et me the length
a[5:] ==> e the length
a[-2:] ==> h
a[-17:] ==> Get me the length
Slicing (post) a[:index] - Get me all string till the specified index. (similar to substring)
a[:1] ==> G
a[:5] ==> Get m
a[:-1] ==> Get me the lengt

Slicing with the step (a[::1])
Having 2 colons in the syntax will let us skip the letter both forward and reverse (using a -ve symbol)

a[::1] ==> Get me the length
a[::3] ==> 'G  eet' (get me every 3rd element of the string including first )
a[::-1] ==> 'htgnel eht em teG'
a[::-3] ==> 'hn tme'


String properties:
  a[0] = 'L' // Errors out as the String is immutable.
  
  + ==> concatenates 
  * ==> Multiplies the String like a for loop.
  a*5 ==>'Get me the lengthGet me the lengthGet me the lengthGet me the lengthGet me the length'
  a.upper() ==> to convert the string to uppercase.
  
  
